   "source": [
    "# The Cars Dataset\n",
    "Here we'll use the classic Cars dataset to illustrate different ways Gumbi can be used."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "081434ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import gumbi as gmb\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use(gmb.style.breve)\n",
    "\n",
    "from warnings import filterwarnings\n",
    "\n",
    "# Suppress a weird warning from seaborn\n",
    "filterwarnings(\"ignore\", message=\"No data for colormapping provided via 'c'. Parameters 'norm' will be ignored\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bf738615",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Read in some data and store it as a Gumbi `DataSet`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "27f6aec1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cars = sns.load_dataset('mpg').dropna().astype({'weight':float, 'model_year':float})\n",
    "\n",
    "ds = gmb.DataSet(cars,\n",
    "                 outputs=['mpg', 'acceleration'],\n",
    "                 log_vars=['mpg', 'acceleration', 'weight', 'horsepower', 'displacement'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15c55de1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Create a Gumbi `GP` object:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "2b9899eb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "gp = gmb.GP(ds)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9868903e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we're ready to fit, predict, and plot against various dimensions in our datset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a5388525",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]

      ]

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = gp.prepare_grid()\n",
    "y = gp.predict_grid();\n",
    "\n",
    "pp = gmb.ParrayPlotter(X, y)\n",
    "pp.plot()\n",
    "sns.scatterplot(data=cars, x='horsepower', y='mpg', color=sns.cubehelix_palette()[-1], alpha=0.5);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a5478cfb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that, despite the error bands appearing wider at lower values of *horsepower*, this actually is a homoskedastic model; i.e., predicted noise does not depend on the input value. However, because we declared *mpg* among the `log_vars` when we defined our `DataSet`, the model is homoskedastic in *log space*. Let's plot `log(mpg)` to illustrate this:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "23186449",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pp.y_scale = 'transformed'\n",
    "pp.y_tick_scale = 'transformed'\n",
    "pp.update()\n",
    "pp.plot()\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.scatterplot(data=cars.assign(mpg=np.log(cars.mpg)), x='horsepower', y='mpg', color=sns.cubehelix_palette()[-1], alpha=0.5);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cc423782",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We declared `horsepower` to be a *log_var* as well. Let's view both `mpg` and `horsepower` in log-space, but retain the natural-space tick labels for easier interpretation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "fd5ab5fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pp.y_tick_scale = 'natural'\n",
    "pp.x_scale = 'transformed'\n",
    "pp.update()\n",
    "pp.plot()\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.scatterplot(data=cars.assign(mpg=np.log(cars.mpg), horsepower=np.log(cars.horsepower)), x='horsepower', y='mpg', color=sns.cubehelix_palette()[-1], alpha=0.5);"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Correlated multivariate sampling from joint predictions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "cb1c4828",
   "metadata": {
    "lines_to_next_cell": 2
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 685.722x500 with 5 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = gp.parray(horsepower=[50, 100, 150, 200])\n",
    "gp.predict_points(X)\n",
    "y = gp.predictions\n",
    "\n",
    "samples_df = pd.concat(\n",
    "    [pd.DataFrame(point.dist.rvs(10000, random_state=j).as_dict()).assign(horsepower=hp.values()) for j, (point, hp) in enumerate(zip(y, X))],\n",
    "    ignore_index=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.pairplot(samples_df, hue='horsepower', kind='kde', corner=True, plot_kws={'levels': 1});"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b8ce3f6f",
   "metadata": {},

    "gp.fit(outputs=['mpg', 'acceleration'], categorical_dims=['origin'], continuous_dims=['horsepower'], linear_dims=['horsepower']);\n",
    "\n",
    "X = gp.prepare_grid()\n",
    "axs = plt.subplots(2,3, figsize=(18, 8))[1]\n",
    "for i, (row, origin) in enumerate(zip(axs.T, cars.origin.unique())):\n",
    "    Y = gp.predict_grid(categorical_levels={'origin': origin})\n",
    "    for ax, output in zip(row, gp.outputs):\n",
    "        y = Y.get(output)\n",
    "\n",
    "        gmb.ParrayPlotter(X, y).plot(ax=ax, palette=sns.light_palette(f'C{i}'))\n",
    "\n",
    "        sns.scatterplot(data=cars[cars.origin==origin], x='horsepower', y=output, color=f'C{i}', alpha=0.5, ax=ax);"
   ]

    "## Multi-dimensional regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "4da29a87",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from matplotlib.colors import Normalize\n",
    "norm = Normalize()\n",
    "norm(ds.wide.mpg);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4cf5a7f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2D regression with and without linear kernel"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ad82b0a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that here we plot the coefficient of variation (with respect to aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty together) as dashed lines."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "a32c6ebf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",

    "cylinders = cars.cylinders.unique()\n",
    "cylinders.sort()\n",
    "\n",
    "axs = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(30, 4.5))[1]\n",
    "    \n",
    "gp.fit(outputs=['mpg'], continuous_dims=['horsepower','weight', 'cylinders'], linear_dims=['horsepower','weight', 'cylinders']);\n",
    "\n",
    "for ax, cyl in zip(axs, cylinders):\n",
    "\n",
    "    XY = gp.prepare_grid(at=gp.parray(cylinders=cyl))\n",
    "    X = XY['horsepower']\n",
    "    Y = XY['weight']\n",
    "    z = gp.predict_grid(with_noise=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.sca(ax)\n",
    "    pp = gmb.ParrayPlotter(X, Y, z)\n",
    "    pp(plt.contourf, levels=20, cmap='pink', norm=norm)\n",
    "    pp.colorbar(ax=ax)\n",
    "\n",
    "    cs = ax.contour(X.values(), Y.values(), z.σ, levels=4, colors='0.2', linestyles='--')\n",
    "    ax.clabel(cs)\n",
    "\n",
    "    sns.scatterplot(data=cars[cars.cylinders==cyl], x='horsepower', y='weight', hue='mpg', palette='pink', norm=norm, ax=ax);\n",
    "    ax.legend().remove()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    title = 'RBF+Linear kernel' if linear else 'RBF kernel'\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f'{cyl} Cylinders')\n",
    "    \n",
    "plt.tight_layout()"
